solutions.content:
**Approach:-**
* The Thief *cannot choose the two adjacent nodes* right?
* Also, If we know the maximum amount the thief can stole for the child and grand child nodes of current node, we can answer the maximum amount for current node also...Guess Why? [Think for above condition].
* Since, *If we choose current node into our answer*, we cannot take the child nodes of the current node right? Hence, **we'd be looking for maximum answer we can get with grand child nodes**.
* When *we don't choose current node into our answer*, **we would look for maximum answer for left as well as right child nodes**.
* **dp[node v] = max(root->val + dp[left grand child of v] + dp[right grand child of v] , dp[left child of v] + dp[right child of v] )** is the dp relation.
* Wait, How we would maintain an array in binary tree?, If you'd notice we want only values for child nodes and grand child nodes right?
* So, we would maintain a **pair<int,int>** for every node **{max ans child nodes, max ans for grand child nodes}** and recursively calculate answer for every node.

```
class Solution {
public:
    // TIME COMPLEXITY:- O(N)
    // SPACE COMPLEXITY:- O(1) [neglecting the extra space due to recursion stack]
    pair<int,int> findMax(TreeNode* root){
        if(!root)
            return {0,0};
        pair<int,int> l = findMax(root->left); // {max ans for left child, max ans for left grand child}
        pair<int,int> r = findMax(root->right); // {max ans for right child, max ans for right grand child}
        return {max(root->val+l.second+r.second,l.first+r.first),l.first+r.first}; // either choose the current node or go with the grand child nodes
    }
    int rob(TreeNode* root) {
        return findMax(root).first; // answer will be the max ans for current node
    }
};
```

