solutions.content:
we define function rob return the maximum amount of money.
**And It will automatically contact the police if two directly-linked houses were broken into on the same night.**

it means that if we choose the value of current node we cannot choose the value of beside node.
so the ans = max(current->val + (**the largest amount of money without choosing the beside node**), **the largest amount of money without choosing the current node**);

how can we find the **the largest amount of money without choosing the beside node**?
for example, if the current node is the root,
**the largest amount of money without choosing the beside node** = rob(current->left->left) + rob(current->left->right) + rob(current->right->left) + rob(current->right->right)
= 3 + 1 = 4.

**how can we simplify it?**
when backtracking, we can use variable sum to store the sum of rob(current->left) and rob(current->right).
and when it backtrack to the parent node, current = parent node. 
And sum = (rob(current->left->left) + rob(current->left->right)) 
or (rob(current->left->left) + rob(current->left->right)).

so when it backtrack to the parent node, we use preSum to store **the largest amount of money without choosing the beside node**.
And the end we return max(root->val + preSum, sum).
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/47b68fc3-a39d-49b2-8ca5-6908125a36ce_1653318138.3652587.png)

```
class Solution {
public:
    int sum = 0;
    int rob(TreeNode* root) {
        if(!root){
            sum = 0;
            return 0;
        }
        int l = rob(root->left);
        int preSum = sum;
        int r = rob(root->right);
        preSum += sum;
        sum = l + r;
        return max(root->val + preSum, sum);
    }
};
```

