solutions.content:
**Explanation**

For a node, there are two possiblities: it will be included (robbed) or not. In the first case, if it is included then its child node (which is directly-linked to it) will not be included. And in the second case, we can maximize the results obtained from both of its child nodes.
So we can use DFS starting from the root node and going in both directions (left & right) till leaf nodes. The return value of DFS function is pair<int, int> - first if the present node is included, second if it isn't.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/11e209ec-3079-4465-b5f7-94b0a9881334_1655126934.092918.jpeg)
TestCase: [1,7,9,2,6,5,11,null,9,5] || Result: 37
<br>
**Code**
``` 
pair<int,int> dfs(TreeNode* n) {
	if(n==NULL) return {0,0}; //null
	if(n->left==NULL && n->right==NULL) return {n->val, 0}; //leaf node ( its value will be (val,0)
	auto l = dfs(n->left), r = dfs(n->right);
	pair<int,int> x;
	x.first = n->val + l.second + r.second; //node included (its children (l&r) are excluded)
	x.second = max(l.first, l.second) + max(r.first, r.second); //node excluded
	return x;
}

int rob(TreeNode* root) {
	auto ans = dfs(root);
	return max(ans.first, ans.second);
}
```

