solutions.content:
This solution takes care of the follow up 1 and also can be extended to follow up 2. 
Notice that a matrix can be shown as
```
 [     [  1, 2, 3, 4],
	 [ 5, 1, 2, 3],
 [  9, 5, 1, 2]]

```
so that in a Toeplitz matrix previous row with range 0..n-2 is equal to the current row with range 1..n -1. Using CRC check sum function we need to calculate only two range sums and unload the current row from memory. Even if a row is so large that it doesn't fit into memory we can load the row partially and calculate CRC sum part by part.

```java
import java.util.zip.CRC32;
class Solution {

    private byte[] toByteArray(int[] arr) {
        byte[] ans = new byte[arr.length];
        for(int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
            ans[i] = (byte) arr[i];
        }
        return ans;
    }

    private long getCheckSum(int[] arr, int from, int to) {
        CRC32 crc = new CRC32();
        crc.update(toByteArray(arr), from, to);
        return crc.getValue();
    }

    public boolean isToeplitzMatrix(int[][] matrix) {
        int m = matrix.length;
        int n = matrix[0].length;
        // load first row
        long checksum = getCheckSum(matrix[0], 0, n - 1);
        // load rows one by one
        for(int row = 1; row < m; row++) {
            if(checksum != getCheckSum(matrix[row], 1, n - 1)){
                return false;
            }
            checksum = getCheckSum(matrix[row], 0, n - 1);
        }
        return true;
    }
}
```

